liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: When asked if he thought the Victorian state government, as supporters of the Voice, could have done more to get its message across to voters, MP Danny Pearson said it was "ultimately a matter for the federal government". He said the state government would continue its work establishing a treaty. "To Indigenous Victorians, I say we love you, we respect you, and we'll work with you to achieve a treaty in this state," he said. "That's the most important thing that's before us now. "We've got a job to do and we're going to get on and we'll deliver treaty for the people of Victoria." He said Victoria was "the most progressive state in the nation" and he was confident achieving a treaty in the state would see other states and territories follow suit. "When we establish a treaty, when we have the practical application of working with First Nations people in this state … it might give other states and other jurisdictions some level of confidence that there's nothing to be frightened [of]," he said. "This is about just listening to people, it's about respecting Indigenous Victorians, it's about working together, walking this journey together side-by-side to a better and a fairer outcome, and it's the right thing to do. "I think that when people see this happening in Victoria, there will be that sense of acceptance, there will be this realisation that the sky is not going to fall in, this is just good public policy."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Victorian MP says state government is determined to establish treaty

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: ABC reporter Isabella Higgins says some Indigenous leaders may have felt "burnt" that their conciliatory message was rejected by Australian voters. She says a shift towards black sovereignty might now have more appeal. "It will change the way Indigenous Australians want to interact with the rest of the country," she says. "It will change whether kindness is the best approach. "I think often in the community it is well understood that black anger is not tolerated, and so we see leaders pull in their rage, pull in their sadness, and constantly use language of geneority, use graciousness to try and appeal to the Australian people. "And after this, I think there will be a generation of leaders who have been burnt by this and who won't be interested in doing that anymore."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Will we see a tone shift from Indigenous activism?

title.children: Repatriation flights from Israel are likely to take off today, Penny Wong says

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Australian Tamara Porat called in from Tel Aviv as she prepared to board a repatriation flight to Dubai from Israel. Foreign Minister Penny Wong has confirmed a mixture of government-chartered and military planes will be leaving Tel Aviv today for Australians wishing to leave. Ms Porat was initially hoping to leave on Friday on a Qantas flight, but wasn't able to make it. "A few flights were meant to leave yesterday, they've all been cancelled," Ms Porat said. She said it was "bittersweet" to be leaving her Israeli family behind to return to Australia. Ms Porat said people at the airport were remaining calm despite the situation. "Everyone is very calm and the queue is progressing slowly, but I think everyone is aware of the situation," she said. "Wishing to leave but no dramas here, everything is moving as planned."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Aussies in Israel wait to board repatriation flights

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Foreign Minister Penny Wong during a press conference in Adelaide said that the travel advice for Lebanon has changed. "The existing travel advice for Lebanon is reconsider your need to travel due to the security environment. "I am now saying to Australians if you are in Lebanon on, you should consider whether your need to remain there is essential," Ms Wong said. "If you wish to leave you should know that a crisis could limit commercial options for departure and you should consider the first available option." If you need emergency consular assistance contact the emergency consular centre operating on a 24-hour basis on 1300 555 135 (within Australia), or +61 2 6261 3305 (from anywhere in the world) .
